items.title: Nataxa flavescens
items.content_text: Moth found resting on decking of house, where it remained for several days.

items.title: Macrobathra spp.
items.content_text: Resting on leaf of juvenile Red Box tree along New Year Dam Track, Brisbane Ranges National Park. Yet to determine to species level. Similar markings to M. euryleuca.

items.title: Oecophoridae spp.
items.content_text: Concealer Moth resting on Prostanthera decussata. Possibly a species of Chysonoma.

items.title: Thalaina selenaea
items.content_text: With white fringed forewing margin, rather than rusty colour.

items.title: Doratifera oxleyi
items.content_text: This is the male of the species, which looks rather dissimilar to the larger female.

items.title: Anthela repleta
items.content_text: In photo 2, the moth has laid eggs on the stem of Pultenaea gunnii subsp. tuberculata.

items.title: Epicyme rubropunctaria
items.content_text:
Geometridae spp.
Possibly Idaea or Scopula spp.

items.title: Mimaglossa nauplialis
items.content_text: Pyralidae spp. Identification thanks to Darren Carman.

items.title: Cosmodes elegans
items.content_text: A rare pale-brown morph of this species.

items.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
items.content_text:
A species of Epicoma.
There were also multiple clusters of eggs on the glass of the windows around the house. They were covered in hair the same colour as the abdominal tuft of the moth.
